<!-- 01 INTRO -->
<section class="section">
  <div class="container narrow">
    <p class="section-number">01, About this service</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">WhisperKool repair across LA — current models, legacy units, and the EPA 608 piece nobody talks about.</h2>

    <p>WhisperKool has been engineering and assembling wine cellar cooling units in Pulaski, Tennessee for over thirty years, and across our five-county LA service area they're the most-installed premium cellar-cooling brand. We see them everywhere: SC Pro Series flagships in newer Beverly Hills and Bel Air wine rooms, Platinum Split systems in Malibu canyon estates with 1,500-bottle collections, Slimline and Mini Ceiling Mount units in West Hollywood and Brentwood condos, and a long tail of XLT-series legacy units in cellars built between 2008 and 2019 that are now reaching the typical end-of-component-life window.</p>

    <p>One thing worth understanding before you call anyone: <strong>WhisperKool work involves regulated refrigerant</strong> — R-134a on most older units, R-410a on some splits, R-513A on current SC Pro production. EPA 608 certification is federally required for any technician opening the refrigerant circuit. Our techs hold EPA 608 Universal (#1346255700410) plus BHGS Registration #A49573 — the exact combination WhisperKool's own "Find a Technician" referral program looks for when they route owners to local service. Many of our WhisperKool calls come in exactly that way: cellar warms up, owner calls WhisperKool support, WhisperKool refers them to a certified local tech, and we get the call.</p>

    <p>This page covers the full WhisperKool lineup we service, the failure patterns we see by series, the LA microclimate context that affects each, and honest repair-versus-replace economics by age and series.</p>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- 02 SERIES — CURRENT -->
<section class="section section-gray">
  <div class="container">
    <p class="section-number">02, Current series</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">Current WhisperKool lineup we service.</h2>

    <p class="lead">Five active product families plus the Vinotheque co-branded units. Each has its own failure tree and its own LA neighborhood concentration.</p>

    <div class="appliance-grid">
      <div class="appliance-card">
        <h3>SC Pro Series — Self-Contained Flagship</h3>
        <p class="model-list">SC Pro 2000 · 3000 · 4000 · 6000 · 8000</p>
        <p>Through-wall self-contained units, replaced the XLT line around 2019. New Intelligent Control Unit (ICU), 45-degree upward blower angle, built-in condensate evaporator with heating element. Most-common service on 5+ year units: ICU board glitches after power events (LA blackouts during fire-season Public Safety Power Shutoffs are a recurring trigger), condensate evaporator heating element burnout around year 7 ($180-$220 part), blower fan bearing whine — early-warning audible, $80-$110 fix if caught before the bearing seizes.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="appliance-card">
        <h3>Platinum Split — Premium Two-Piece</h3>
        <p class="model-list">Platinum Split 4000 · 8000 · 12000 · 18000</p>
        <p>Most common in Beverly Hills, Malibu, and Bel Air estates with 1,500-4,000 cubic-foot cellars. Indoor evaporator + outdoor condenser, lowest cellar-side noise in the WhisperKool lineup (around 50dB at the cellar). Most common service: refrigerant leak at lineset flare connections (especially on installs done by general HVAC contractors without dedicated WhisperKool training), indoor evaporator condensate drain clog (urgent — water plus humidity in a wine cellar is mold risk on cabinetry), outdoor condenser fan motor failure from sun and heat exposure on rooftop installs.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="appliance-card">
        <h3>Slimline + Ceiling Mount</h3>
        <p class="model-list">Slimline 1700 · 2500 · 3500 · 4000 · Mini Ceiling Mount 2500/4000/6000 · Ceiling Mount 4000/6000/8000</p>
        <p>Most common in Westwood, Brentwood, and West Hollywood condos with smaller 800-1,500 cubic-foot cellars. Slimline 2500 is the workhorse for 1,000 cu ft residential cellars. Common ceiling-mount issues: compressor vibration transmitting through ceiling joists (isolators degrade around year 6-8), drain-line freeze on undersized Mini Ceiling Mount installs, filter neglect leading to coil freeze-up. Annual maintenance prevents the freeze-up failure entirely.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="appliance-card">
        <h3>Extreme Series — High-Capacity Stainless</h3>
        <p class="model-list">Extreme 3500ti · 5000ti · 8000ti (current) · Extreme 3000/4000/6000 (legacy)</p>
        <p>Used in larger 3,000+ cu ft cellars, uninsulated spaces, or hot-climate installations. The "ti" suffix on current production indicates stainless-steel components — marine-grade, relevant for Malibu coastal humidity. High-stress operation tends to age the compressor faster than self-contained or split alternatives; we typically see compressor wear at 8-10 years on Extreme units installed in genuinely uninsulated cellar spaces, longer if the cellar envelope is properly insulated and the ambient is moderate.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="appliance-card">
        <h3>Ducted SC — Multi-Room</h3>
        <p class="model-list">Ducted SC 4000 · 6000 · 8000</p>
        <p>Self-contained units with duct connections, used to cool tasting rooms and adjacent storage from a single mechanical closet. Service tree mostly tracks the standard SC Pro plus duct-side issues: insulated duct sleeve degradation at year 7-10, supply-grille condensate dripping from improperly insulated runs, balancing-damper drift causing room-to-room temperature variance.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="appliance-card">
        <h3>Vinotheque Co-Branded</h3>
        <p class="model-list">Same internals as standard WhisperKool, badged Vinotheque</p>
        <p>Vinotheque sources WhisperKool engines for their boutique-cabinet cellars and brands them as their own. We service these identically to standard WhisperKool — same compressor, same control logic, same failure modes. Common in Vinotheque-built cellar installations across West Hollywood and Beverly Hills.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- 03 LEGACY -->
<section class="section">
  <div class="container">
    <p class="section-number">03, Legacy units still in service</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">XLT and original-series WhisperKool — discontinued, but still serviceable.</h2>

    <p class="lead">Plenty of LA cellars built between 2008 and 2019 still run discontinued WhisperKool units. We keep parts in inventory for the most common ones because they keep showing up on the schedule.</p>

    <ul class="bullet-list">
      <li><strong>XLT Series (XLT 1600 · 3000 · 4200 · 6000):</strong> Discontinued around 2019 in favor of SC Pro. Used the PDT (Programmable Digital Thermostat) controller — a known failure cluster around year 7-10. Two service paths on a thermostat-only failure: OEM PDT replacement, or retrofit with a modern digital thermostat that gives you another 3-5 years on an otherwise-fine chassis. Compressor end-of-life on XLT units typically arrives at year 10-12 in LA, and that's the point where the repair-versus-replace conversation usually tips toward replacement.</li>
      <li><strong>Original Extreme (3000 · 4000 · 6000, pre-ti):</strong> Older non-stainless Extreme line, mostly 2010-2015 installs. Coastal corrosion on these is the real end-of-life event — Malibu units especially. We can repair, but the chassis is the cost-driver after 10 years.</li>
      <li><strong>Original SC Series (SC 2500 · 4000 · 6000, pre-Pro):</strong> Pre-2019 self-contained units. Same architecture concept as current SC Pro, less sophisticated control. Replacement parts available for several more years; compressor and fan-motor service still feasible.</li>
    </ul>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- 04 COMMON FAILURES -->
<section class="section section-gray">
  <div class="container">
    <p class="section-number">04, What goes wrong</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">WhisperKool failure patterns we see across LA.</h2>

    <ul class="bullet-list">
      <li><strong>Cellar climbing temperature (most common):</strong> First diagnostic is always the condenser coil. About 40% of our WhisperKool service calls resolve at deep clean plus airflow check, no parts. $150-$250 service call. We don't oversell — if the unit is fine after cleaning, that's the report.</li>
      <li><strong>Refrigerant leak (split systems):</strong> Visible signs — rising cellar temps with the unit clearly running, ice formation on the lineset. EPA 608 work: pressure test, leak isolation, repair, recharge. Most common cause is improper installation flare connections by non-certified contractors, or lineset damage during home renovation work years after the original install.</li>
      <li><strong>ICU / PDT controller faults:</strong> SC Pro units throw alarm codes on the ICU after power surges; XLT units lose the PDT thermostat outright. Replacement runs $280-$450 with labor; XLT retrofit option mentioned above.</li>
      <li><strong>Condensate drain issues:</strong> Water backing up into the cellar or pooling near the unit. Causes: drain line clog, condensate evaporator failure on SC Pro (heating element burnout), pump failure if a pump is in the install. Urgent — water plus wine cellar humidity creates mold conditions on cabinetry quickly.</li>
      <li><strong>Compressor end-of-life:</strong> Year 10-15 on most series. We quote both the compressor replacement and a brand-new SC Pro install before you authorize anything; on 12-plus-year units, customers often choose the new unit because of the warranty reset and ICU upgrade.</li>
    </ul>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- 05 RECENT REPAIRS -->
<section class="section">
  <div class="container">
    <p class="section-number">05, Recent repairs</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">WhisperKool jobs from across the territory.</h2>

    <p class="lead">Four representative WhisperKool service calls — model, symptom, diagnosis, repair, and outcome. Names and addresses omitted; the technical scenarios are typical of what we see on WhisperKool across each environment.</p>

    <div class="repair-grid">
      <div class="repair-card">
        <h3>Platinum Split 8000, Beverly Hills estate cellar</h3>
        <p><strong>Symptom:</strong> Owner reported cellar warmed from 55°F to 68°F over a three-week window with the unit clearly still running. 1,200-bottle collection. About 9 years on the install.</p>
        <p><strong>Diagnosis:</strong> Pressure test revealed slow refrigerant loss on the indoor evaporator coil — pinhole leak at a hairpin bend, consistent with the age and the cellar's daily thermal cycling. Outdoor condenser tested clean.</p>
        <p><strong>Repair:</strong> EPA 608 evacuation and recovery, leak repair at the affected coil section, full R-134a recharge to spec, system pressure-tested over a one-hour run cycle. Cellar back to 55°F within 24 hours.</p>
        <p><strong>Cost:</strong> $645 total. Same-day, on-site about 2.5 hours.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="repair-card">
        <h3>SC Pro 4000, Malibu canyon estate</h3>
        <p><strong>Symptom:</strong> ICU showing intermittent alarm codes after a winter power-shutoff event during a Pacific Coast storm. Unit cycling but not maintaining setpoint reliably.</p>
        <p><strong>Diagnosis:</strong> ICU board passed initial diagnostics but logged surge-related fault codes. Power-event damage on the controller side, common after PSPS events and storm-related outages.</p>
        <p><strong>Repair:</strong> ICU board replacement with OEM unit, full system parameter reset, verified setpoint stability across a 90-minute test. Recommended a surge-protection install at the panel for the cellar circuit.</p>
        <p><strong>Cost &amp; time:</strong> $485 total. 75 minutes on-site.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="repair-card">
        <h3>XLT 3000, Bel Air 2012-built cellar</h3>
        <p><strong>Symptom:</strong> Original PDT thermostat went dark, no display, no system control. Unit was 8 years old — exactly on the typical PDT failure schedule.</p>
        <p><strong>Diagnosis:</strong> PDT confirmed dead at the controller. Compressor and refrigerant circuit tested clean, fan motors normal. Customer wanted to keep the XLT chassis rather than replace the full system.</p>
        <p><strong>Repair:</strong> Retrofit with modern digital thermostat compatible with the XLT chassis. Full system test, setpoint calibration, verified normal cycling. Estimated 3-5 additional years of service on the unit.</p>
        <p><strong>Cost &amp; time:</strong> $385 total. 60 minutes on-site.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="repair-card">
        <h3>Slimline 2500, Brentwood condo</h3>
        <p><strong>Symptom:</strong> Cellar climbing past 60°F over a hot week, owner worried the unit was failing. About 6 years on the install in a closet behind the wine room.</p>
        <p><strong>Diagnosis:</strong> No mechanical fault — heavy dust accumulation on the condenser coil was blocking heat dissipation. Installation closet ambient airflow was also restricted by storage that had built up over the years.</p>
        <p><strong>Repair:</strong> Full condenser coil deep clean, drain line flush, verified ambient airflow in the install closet, advised the owner on storage clearance. Cellar back to 55°F same day.</p>
        <p><strong>Cost &amp; time:</strong> $185 total, no parts. 50 minutes on-site.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- 06 LA CONTEXT -->
<section class="section section-gray">
  <div class="container narrow">
    <p class="section-number">06, Where we see WhisperKool in LA</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">WhisperKool installs across the LA wine country.</h2>

    <p>The WhisperKool footprint across our service area concentrates by neighborhood. <strong>Beverly Hills</strong> and <strong>Bel Air</strong> are dominated by Platinum Split units in 1,500-4,000 cu ft wine rooms, with SC Pro 6000 and 8000 self-contained units showing up in newer construction. <strong>Malibu</strong> canyon estates lean toward Extreme ti series — the stainless components matter against coastal salt air, and the higher BTU capacity matters against summer canyon heat. <strong>Pacific Palisades</strong> runs smaller boutique cellars, mostly Slimline and Ceiling Mount range. <strong>Hollywood Hills</strong> still has a meaningful number of vintage 1990s-2000s cellars with original pre-Pro SC Series units; these are increasingly replacement candidates rather than repair targets.</p>

    <p><strong>West Hollywood</strong> and Mid-Wilshire condos lean toward the smaller end — Mini Ceiling Mount 2500 and 4000 are popular for the under-1,000 cu ft cellars common in luxury condo conversions. <strong>Brentwood</strong> splits between Platinum Split installs in newer estates and XLT legacy units in 1990s-2010s estate construction.</p>

    <p>LA microclimates matter for sizing and for service cadence. The Hills neighborhoods see 95°F+ summer stretches that demand oversized capacity to maintain 55°F cellar setpoints; coastal Malibu sees salt-air corrosion on outdoor split condensers; inland Hollywood Hills sees the highest dust load on condenser coils because of canyon-airflow patterns. We size, install, and maintain with the specific microclimate in mind.</p>
  </div>
</section>

